lattice3dnlshell.out
Shell-mode lattice3dnl (shellnormal-tagged rectangle, large rotations): tension + axial twist; exercises J = b*t^3/12.
StaticStructural nsteps 3 rtolv 1.e-6 ddm 4 2 1 2 4 ddv 2 1.e-4 1.e-3 ddltf 2 nmodules 1
errorcheck
domain 3dLattice
OutputManager tstep_all dofman_all element_all
ndofman 2 nelem 1 ncrosssect 1 nmat 1 nbc 1 nic 0 nltf 2
node 1 coords 3 0.000000e+00 0.000000e+00 0.000000e+00 bc 6 1 1 1 1 1 1
node 2 coords 3 1.000000e+00 0.000000e+00 0.000000e+00 bc 6 0 0 0 0 0 0
lattice3Dnl 1 nodes 2 1 2 crossSect 1 mat 1 shellnormal 3 0.0 0.0 1.0 polycoords 12 0.5 -0.05 -0.005   0.5 0.05 -0.005   0.5 0.05 0.005   0.5 -0.05 0.005
latticecs 1 material 1
latticeframeelastic 1 d 2400. tAlpha 0.0 E 30.e9 n 0.0
BoundaryCondition 1 loadTimeFunction 1 prescribedvalue 0.0
ConstantFunction 1 f(t) 1.
PiecewiseLinFunction 2 nPoints 2 t 2 1. 4. f(t) 2 0. 1.
#%BEGIN_CHECK% tolerance 1.e-3
## Step 3: load factor = 2/3, prescribed disp = 6.667e-5 m, prescribed twist = 6.667e-4 rad.
## Reaction at clamped node 1, dof 1 = axial force        = -E*eps*A    = -2.0e3   N
## Reaction at clamped node 1, dof 4 = torsion moment     = -G*J*twist  = -8.333e-2 N*m
## with shell J = b*t^3/12 (plate-twisting form) and G = E/2 at nu=0.
## The dof-4 reaction pins down the shell J formula (shellnormal-driven);
## the generic-polygon fallback (J = Ip) would yield ~100x larger.
## Large-rotation form (lattice3dnl) at this prescribed magnitude is numerically
## indistinguishable from the small-rotation form (lattice3dshell.in twin).
#REACTION tStep 3 number 1 dof 1 value -2.0000e+3
#REACTION tStep 3 number 1 dof 4 value -8.3333e-2
#%END_CHECK%
